Author Name: **Dan Gisselquist**
Original Redmine Message: 2282 from https://www.veripool.org



---

Feature request ...

Consider the following code snippet:

```<code class="text">
module tst(i_clk, i_val, o_a, o_b);
         input   wire    i_clk;
         input   wire    i_val;
         output  reg     o_a, o_b;

         always @(posedge i_clk)
                 if ((i_val)&&(!o_a))
                         o_b <= 1'b0;

         always @(posedge i_clk)
                 if ((i_val)&&(o_a))
                         o_b <= 1'b1;

         always @(posedge i_clk)
                 o_a <= i_val;

endmodule
</code>
```

Notice that o_b is being assigned in two separate always blocks, to contradictory values.

Verilator, running with -Wall, doesn't catch this.  Instead, it happily creates a C++ program that assigns to o_b twice.

How hard would it be to modify Verilator to detect this situation?

Thanks!

Dan
